   "source": [
    "## Logs ¥u2014 `journalctl` and `/var/log`¥n",
    "¥n",
    "systemd ships its own log daemon, **`systemd-journald`**, which collects messages from the kernel, every service, and every session into one **structured binary journal**. You read it with **`journalctl`**. The win over `tail`-ing eight files: one unified log with metadata (unit, PID, priority) and powerful filtering.¥n",
    "¥n",
    "```bash¥n",
    "journalctl -u nginx              # everything for nginx.service¥n",
    "journalctl -u nginx -f           # follow live (like tail -f)¥n",
    "journalctl -u nginx --since ¥"1 hour ago¥"¥n",
    "journalctl -p err                # priority: errors and worse (0 emerg ¥u2026 7 debug)¥n",
    "journalctl -b                    # this boot only   (-b -1 = previous boot)¥n",
    "journalctl -k                    # kernel messages (a dmesg replacement)¥n",
    "```¥n",
    "¥n",
    "¥u26a0¥ufe0f **Persistent vs volatile:** by default many distros keep the journal in `/run` ¥u2014 **tmpfs, wiped on reboot**. Create **`/var/log/journal/`** (or set `Storage=persistent` in `journald.conf`) and journald keeps history across reboots. Cap its size with `SystemMaxUse=1G`, or trim with `journalctl --vacuum-time=2weeks`.¥n",
    "¥n",
    "**Traditional logs in `/var/log/` still matter** ¥u2014 many services write there directly, and `rsyslog` mirrors the journal into plain files. Know **`/var/log/syslog`** (Debian) / **`messages`** (RHEL) for general messages, **`auth.log`** / **`secure`** for logins and sudo, and **`dmesg`** for the kernel ring buffer. Growing logs are kept in check by **`logrotate`** (config in `/etc/logrotate.d/`), which renames, compresses, and expires old logs ¥u2014 usually triggered by a daily timer.¥n"
   ]
  }
